              "claim_supported": "biological problem and signal-response framework"
            }
          ],
          "text_runs": [
            {
              "text": "The lecture frames the response as a control problem in which a defined signal must be detected, converted into intracellular change and translated into altered physiology. ",
              "source_type": "lecture_slide_core",
              "source_anchor": "fixture_lecture_slides.pdf slides 10-11",
              "highlight": "none",
              "in_text_citation": null
            },
            {
              "text": "The uploaded reading chapter refines this by showing that signal duration can alter the stability of the downstream state, so timing as well as amplitude affects the final response. ",
              "source_type": "extra_reading_book",
              "source_anchor": "fixture_extra_reading.pdf chapter 2 section signal duration",
              "highlight": "yellow",
              "in_text_citation": null
            },
            {
              "text": "Together, the lecture and reading support an essay argument in which control is explained as a sequence from detection to mechanism to consequence.",
              "source_type": "lecture_slide_core",
              "source_anchor": "fixture_lecture_slides.pdf slide 11",
              "highlight": "none",
              "in_text_citation": null
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "paragraph_id": "H2",
          "function": "heading",
          "is_heading": true,
          "lecture_anchors": [],
          "text_runs": [
            {
              "text": "2 Mechanism and evidence",
              "source_type": "student_visible_transition",
              "source_anchor": null,
              "highlight": "none",
              "in_text_citation": null
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "paragraph_id": "P2",
          "function": "mechanism",
          "lecture_anchors": [
            {
              "file": "fixture_lecture_slides.pdf",
              "slide_or_page_range": "slides 12-14",
              "lecture_id": "L1",
              "kp_id": "KP01",
              "claim_supported": "mechanism, evidence and consequence"
            }
          ],
          "text_runs": [
            {
              "text": "Mechanistically, the signal acts through a receptor-level decision step ",
              "source_type": "lecture_slide_core",
              "source_anchor": "fixture_lecture_slides.pdf slides 12-13",
              "highlight": "none",
              "in_text_citation": null
            },
            {
              "text": "at a receptor phosphorylation site (Author et al., 2026)",
              "source_type": "citation_original_source",
              "source_anchor": "Author et al. 2026 original paper, read section receptor activation",
              "highlight": "green",
              "in_text_citation": "(Author et al., 2026)",
              "citation_original_read": true,
              "micro_detail_insert": true,
              "original_phrase": "receptor-level decision step",
              "inserted_phrase": "at a receptor phosphorylation site",
              "claim_delta": "precision_only",
              "qa_status": "micro_detail_verified"
            },
            {
              "text": " that constrains which downstream pathway becomes active. This explains why the same tissue can remain stable under weak stimulation but shift state when the signal crosses a threshold. ",
              "source_type": "lecture_slide_core",
              "source_anchor": "fixture_lecture_slides.pdf slides 12-13",
              "highlight": "none",
              "in_text_citation": null
            },
            {
              "text": "A lecture-cited experiment showed that blocking the receptor prevented the downstream transition, supporting a causal rather than merely correlative relationship (Author et al., 2026). ",
              "source_type": "citation_original_source",
              "source_anchor": "Author et al. 2026 original paper, read section Results",
              "highlight": "green",
              "in_text_citation": "(Author et al., 2026)",
              "citation_original_read": true
            },
            {
              "text": "The consequence is that the physiological response can be explained as regulated conversion of signal information into a coordinated output, rather than as an isolated endpoint. The answer therefore stays focused on the causal chain from signal detection to pathway selection and functional interpretation, including the threshold logic that makes weak and strong stimulation produce different outcomes.",
              "source_type": "lecture_slide_core",
              "source_anchor": "fixture_lecture_slides.pdf slide 14",
              "highlight": "none",
              "in_text_citation": null
            }
          ]
        }
